A DC motor with encoder is widely used in robotics and automation because it not only rotates but also gives feedback about speed, direction, and position. Let’s break down the pin configuration clearly and fully 👇




1. What is a DC Motor Encoder?
A DC motor encoder is a normal DC motor attached with an encoder sensor (usually optical or magnetic).
It provides pulses when the motor shaft rotates.
These pulses help measure:
Speed (RPM),
Direction,
Position (angle).

2. Typical Pin Configuration (Most Common Types)

A DC motor encoder usually has 4 to 6 pins, depending on the model.
A. Motor Power Pins (2 pins)

These are for driving the motor itself:

M+ (Motor Positive)
M− (Motor Negative)
Function:

Apply voltage → motor rotates
Reverse polarity → motor reverses direction
B. Encoder Power Pins (2 pins)
VCC (Power Supply) → usually 3.3V or 5V
GND (Ground)
Function:

Supplies power to the encoder circuit
C. Encoder Signal Pins (2 pins – Quadrature Output)
Channel A (OUT A)
Channel B (OUT B)
Function:

These generate digital pulses
Used to detect:
Speed
Direction
3. How Channel A & B Work (Very Important)

The encoder uses a concept called:
Quadrature Encoding

Channel A and B produce square waves
They are 90° out of phase
Meaning:
If A leads B → clockwise rotation
If B leads A → anticlockwise rotation
Example Signal Behavior
Rotation	Signal Pattern
Clockwise	A → B
Anti-clockwise	B → A
4. Types of Encoders in DC Motors
Incremental Encoder (Most common)
Gives pulses only
Needs counting to determine position
Absolute Encoder
Gives exact position directly
More expensive
5. Pulses Per Revolution (PPR)
Encoder gives pulses for each rotation
Example:
100 PPR → 100 pulses per full rotation
Example Connection (Arduino)
M+ / M− → Motor driver (like L298N)
VCC → 5V
GND → GND
A → Digital pin 2 (interrupt)
B → Digital pin 3 (interrupt)
More PPR = higher accuracy
Final Simple View
A DC motor encoder has two parts:

Motor pins (2) → to rotate motor
Encoder pins (4) → to sense motion
